segments.text: Joe Chow, Assistant Planning Director for the City of Houston.
This is the 12th of June, 1987.
Joe, would you please recount how you got into planning, and then go from that point to where you are now, and how this involves the City of Houston?
How I got into planning?
I just happened to land a job with the department.
Well, I guess... How did you go into... Why did you study planning?
Okay, I graduated from Texas A&M with a master's planning program in 1972.
I finished my degree in the summer session and was looking for a job, and one of the places that I applied for a job was the city of Houston planning department, and at that time they had
happened to have a vacancy, and I started as a planner, too, in charge of, or at least I was right away assigned to downtown planning.
And at that time, they were doing some reports for downtown, and I picked up on that.
Identifying the existing conditions, making projections of the employment population,
and checking out the current development and things like that.
Really, it's more like a data book, so to speak.
It's what's going on rather than try to do a downtown plan, so to speak.
Roscoe Jones was the director then.
Roscoe Jones was the director.
That's correct.
I guess...

Because of the nature of planning in Houston at that time, our hands were tied to a certain extent that we would do reports that would spend more time on the current conditions and pointing out possibly some of the problems that exist.
To a certain extent, we recommended
identification solution, but not in the recommendation form.
Some action should be taken, so to speak.
That was during the fast growth area of Houston.
Well, the 72 is growing not as fast as it was in the later part of the 70s and early part of the 80s.
Sort of the beginning of that, right?
The beginning, yeah.
And so through that, I
Also did some parks planning, area planning reports, such as the Galleria data books, so to speak.
We were very careful as to not identify any publication of the plans, so to speak, because we were under the impression that anything
identified as a plan with the public interest or opposition, so to speak, that we're really trying to get something going.
I'm not saying that that posture is totally wrong, but to me, it's probably the policy that's filtering down from the mayor's office at that time.
Who was the mayor?
First it was through Welsh, and then it was Hawthorne, and then it was Jim McComb.
Of course, when Mayor Whitmire came in, she quickly changed the planning director to Ethan Boise, which was about a year.
I think about a year after she searched the country for the planning director,
And Roscoe was quite near retirement at that time, wasn't he?
Roscoe had 18 years in the department.
As far as I know, about 18 or something around there.
Well, the policy, is it 20 years that you get retirement?
You can get retirement with 10 years and attain a certain age.
I see.
Probably when Roscoe...
leave the department.
He was not old enough to actually get retirement benefit, but I think he's invested.
So when he attained his own age, he would probably draw retirement for the 18 or so years.
That's interesting.
But Whitmer wanted her own man in as planning director.
Well, I'm sure everybody knows that
Mayor Whitmire had identified that she wants to run the city like a business corporation.
And she had her own idea and policies of how the city should be run.
And she quickly moved to study how various departments could be more efficient and that the whole system of the city employees could be

reorganized and there was a commission appointed to do studies about various departments how they work together or how they haven't been working together and so on and there was a report out to uh we organized the city department into four or five major city departments putting together some of them and the first one that was
put together was finance administration, combining tax department and some general services or some other departments.
I don't even know what the names were at that time anymore.
And then I think the second one is probably the planning department.
We took over the economic development office of the mayor.
We took over, okay, when finance administration was formed,
the mayor's policy planning department was absorbed by that particular department.
Was that the one that Rick Gerlach was in?
Yes.
And then we later on took over community development.
It's a department with about 120 employees.
Oh.
At the time when Roscoe left, we were about 55 to 60 employees.
So we have taken on a whole lot more responsibility and picked up a lot more employees.
As I remember, the chief activity of the planning department under Roscoe was subdivision processing.
You're probably right.
However, we do have at that time, when I first joined the department, there were four divisions.
Development, coordination, handling plants, and development.
And the major system right away and stuff like that.
And then we have a group called research division, which handles population estimates.
and work with the census and employment estimates and projections.
Economics.
Yeah, and we don't have that much on economics, so to speak, but coordination with the Chamber of Commerce Research Division.
We then also did some land use studies.
That would be Louis Welch, wouldn't it?
Mayor Welch was still with the city at the time, but...
The Chamber of Commerce historically has a very strong research division, and they were very strong in working with the census and population estimates and so on and so forth.
In fact, every year they used to put out a data sheet that estimated the population for the city and the county every year.
plus employment and so on.
So they always have a very good research division, so to speak.
And we have a small group of planners, two at a time, works with them and so on.
And then we have a comprehensive planning division also.
That division works
on items such as downtown reports and also small areas planning reports.
We did also pick up on parks.
We work with parks department and we did some fairly good report.
In fact, there were a lot
better reports came out before I got here than after I did it.
I don't know if that has anything to do with me or not.
In about 1980 there was some work that was done here that took an overall view of the greater Houston area.
Yes, we have been publishing a one-page map with
summary back up on the back page.
The first one we did was called 1990 map.
We didn't want to call it a plan.
I noticed.
Which identified the growth of Houston.
I think it was done during the early 70s or even late 60s.
Identifying how
projected growth would take place, identifying the major regional shopping centers where they would fall on the intersection of major freeways and thoroughfare and so on and so forth.
And the major transportation facilities.
And the major transportation facilities such as freeways, which the information is available from the highway department, so to speak.
documented it all into one piece of document.
You know that when Ralph Ellefrit was the planning director, that the planning department did the freeway planning.
That's correct.
That's what turned to be the major trophies map, probably.
And then later on, it was taken over by the highway people.
Well, we still have the major trophy mapping
responsibility.
It is now part of the development ordinance.
In fact, every time we update the major thoroughfare map, we would have to have council approval on it since 1977.
Now that, I would say that development ordinance would probably be one of the major piece of work that is done under the direction of Oscar Jones.
That much credit, I think, he deserves.
Well, now Joe, does that mean that the city council actually makes the selection of corridors or freeways?
That means the staff will recommend the layout of major streets, so to speak, at a mile distance grid type of
and identifying the need for right-of-ways.
Major streets but not freeways?
No.
Freeways, I think we work with the highway department to identify the location.
That way for areas that's not developed, we would have some basis to
to ensure that when they come in with a plaque, we would request them for dedication of the right-of-ways for major streets and so on.
And we adhere pretty much to it through the years.
And it has been, even before it became an ordinance, it was pretty much followed by the developer and required by the lending
Why not?
Right.
So that we could make sure that we could get from one place to another in the future.
Sure.
Yeah, well, that was quite a change, though, from Ellifrit's administration to Jones, in the sense that under Ellifrit, the planning
Department actually had responsibility for selection of freeway corridors.
Well, there again is probably because of the growth of the Highway Department, too.
Oh, I think so.
It just happened all over the state.
Responsibility just becomes distributed to the District 12 here, and also plus the creation of Houston-Galveston Regional Transit Study Group out of the District 12.
They would have specific responsibility to
identifying, analyzing, and determining the major freeways between Metropolitan Houston and Galveston area.
So I wouldn't say that because we didn't want to do it, but there is a distribution of responsibility.
It just evolved that way.
Right, it just evolved that way.
And also as I was describing the divisions, Mayor McCann did
later on created a neighborhood planning division, which takes care of inner city area.
Of course, 1974, we got into the community development and start getting community development money.
And of course, the mayor created a CD office at the mayor's office.
But the basic area planning
type of function was given to the neighborhood planning division of the planning department at the time.
So we did sort of divided the planning function in areas.
The CD area belonging to the neighborhood planning group, while the rest of the area belonging to the comprehensive planning group, so to speak.
And also the posture of the comprehensive planning group is we would be also responsible for the
general planning of the area.
As a result, we would feel like that the 1990 map was reasonably successful in identifying the growth of the city, the growth of actually the metro area which covers the ETJ outside the city limit.
A lot of the regional shopping centers did fall within very close to the identified location.
Now, if you look at it from today, you might think that the 1990 map might have dictated the location, but I think rather than dictating its influence in the decision,
off the developer to take a better look at why the department had given that location as a regional shopping center or whatever.
Does the department have any plans for doing that sort of map again?
We did in the mid-70s.
worked that 1990 map into a year 2000, okay?
And with that, at that time, it was partly handing over to me as the division chief.
We feel like that maybe the one-page map plus a limited explanation on the back was not sufficient.
We have gone through the progression of coming back to look at things a little bit more

closely so to speak and with the development of some parks master plan and so on and so forth and some other report that has not been published but being used in-house we feel like that maybe we should develop a report that may not be called comprehensive plan but we'll have all the comprehensive planning elements in the report as a result
we did publish a 350-page report called Year 2000 Report.
I'm not sure if you have seen it, but copies were sent...
Copies were sent to the various planning libraries and all the public libraries in Houston.
Now, this one happened to have a cover that was not printed, but we did...
make two prints of that, I think each time 1,000 copies.
And we have distributed all of them at the cost of $10 a copy, except to public agencies.
And in fact, today I have a request from an individual wanting to buy one of these reports.
That's why I have it out on my desk.
They want to read it.
In fact, I was told that TSU used it
sort of a reference book for one of the planning classes.
So in the Houston year 2000 map report, you're stressing data rather than maps.
Right.
Why is that?
We feel like the map would be the one that would come out as a composite map called Houston year 2000 map.
And the report is to, I think,
to really detail the map itself.
Detail the map.
Right.
And to provide, for example, population numbers and projections and so on and so forth.
I think we do have a section on economy at that time.
And of course, since it's being produced at a time when the growth was, like you said, very strong,
point out something that is not happening like this because the economic downturn.
But really, there have not been that much projected into the future, so to speak, even though we call it a year 2000 report.
We did identify what may or should, would happen in certain areas, but not everything.
Okay.
Okay, following up on this is that when
Ephraim Garcia came to be the department director.
He brought with him an idea that he wants to do planning in Houston, which sort of coincides very strongly with my thinking of philosophy about planning in Houston.
We understand that we will not have zoning
but zoning is not planning.
People try to bring that together and confuse the two things.
We, I guess, as professionals, if we can call ourselves that, that we need to identify that zoning is not planning, that zoning is only part of two to maybe accomplish a plan and so on.
And so we feel like that maybe
we could do comprehensive plan for this area here.
And we do feel like that the time has come because of the high growth and all the confusion that is generated through there.
And also, I'm sure, the economic turn down in Texas.
Right.
And the timing is probably quite good at this time for us to do that.
So we started in Houston to work on a set of first we wanted
everybody to be comfortable with the idea of doing climate.
So Ephraim Garcia started talking with a group of area associations.
If you know what area associations are, they are the association joined together by developers and landowners.
For example, there is a city of Post Oak Association, now it's called Uptown.
There's a very strong group called West Houston Association.
South Main Center, and so on and so forth.
At the time, there were about seven area associations with strong financial backing from developers and landowners.
Each one of them really have an executive director who is a professional planner and understand what planning is all about.
And they worked very hard to bring some of the ideas into the office and into the area.
For example, West Houston has been very strong in the area of transportation, which they feel like they need to have before they even go develop the area.
So they were very effective.
Jack Lindahl.
Wasn't Jack Lindahl involved?
Jack Lindahl was... Lindahl.
Yeah, Jack Lindahl was...
the first executive director for West Houston, and then following that, what's his name, now with Chamber of Commerce.
Where is Jack, though?
Jack is now with Bernard Johnson, Senior Vice President for Projects and Planning.
So, just like
Uptown Association, which is City of Posto now, has John Breeding, who's a classmate from Texas A&M.
And then let's see who else.
We do have, okay, South Main Center has Marty Reiner, who's got a Ph.D. in planning, I believe.
So we have very strong backgrounds going into these area associations.
Ifram saw the opportunity to sort of piggyback on their experience and expertise.
We started talking with the area associations, asking them to see if they want to do some comprehensive plans for the areas that they are responsible for.
We have gotten good response from them.
Five out of seven area associations have signed a memorandum of understanding to work with us.
Do you provide them with any kind of guidelines?
We do.
We provide them with guidelines.
In fact, we even provided them with an outline of the report that we want to see from them.
Could I get a copy of that?
Yes, I'm sure somewhere around here we have.
Good.
The evolution is such.
When we first talk with them, we want them to do the report.
We want them to identify the boundary of their study area.

We want them to work with one of our planners or coordinate, hopefully, between the various area associations so that one area association that identify as something to do may not negate something that's happening
another area association.
Of course, you know, this is very similar to what Fort Worth started quite a few years ago on their sector planning.
It's very possible.
I'm not aware of how they go about whether they ask the local group to do it or whether the planning department does it.
Well, the local group does it and then it's coordinated with the professional planning.
Okay, that's probably what we have in mind from the very beginning.
So we start
to go out and sell these ideas to the local residents, so to speak.
And we have gotten the attention of local AIA group, APA group, ACME, everybody.
In fact, when we gotten the signature of the area associations, either the chairman or president or executive director, each time it generated quite a
quite a bit of debate within that area association.

As a result, it also generated a lot of debate within the professional groups in Houston, and Ephraim and myself have been to various meetings to explain to them what we want to do and how we go about doing it.
The situation is such that there are a number

major developers that feel like that they do not understand the process enough or they misunderstood that as a forerunner of the planning department wanting to put more control over how development should be carried out and maybe changing to zoning of the area, so to speak.
And that sort of really caused everybody to pay attention to what we were doing.

uh the chamber of commerce came out at the very beginning as an opposing to this whole process uh you from advanced to various meeting with them finally we have assured them that that's not what we want to do we want to do comprehensive planning we want to take a look at the present and project into the future so that development may be

a little bit more how should i say it orderly so to speak and when the growth and development does come back economically worldwide we can also handle it physically so to speak um and one other thing was one thing i wanted to ask you uh joe um

You know, assuming that all of these neighborhood groups or community groups get their plans together and they're coordinated, presumably, by professional planners from the staff, I've always referred to that method or that style of planning as cut-and-paste method.
And it was tried in Anchorage, Alaska, I think, first of all, about 19...
56 or 57, and I perceive some disadvantages to the method, and I'm sure you do too, but these can be overcome, and I suppose that you and Ephraim have discussed this, and also I wanted to ask you
Once all of these have been put together and you do have, in fact, a bona fide comprehensive plan, then how do you intend to implement it?
Okay.
Things have changed since our initial conception of how these cut-and-paste plans were done.
Because of the various discussions with
the professional group with the developers, with the individuals who are interested.
We have evolved to a situation where now the area association will be supporting the planning department in doing a sector planning.
We will be dividing up the city and its ETJ into two major portions.
One portion is still the CD area.
The planning for that area we perceive as slightly different from the rest of the area.
For CD, we are really going back into identifying the problem, identifying the redevelopment opportunities, so to speak.
And for the rest of the area, we are looking at how to cope with new development.
how to support the new development with the infrastructure that's needed, with the transportation system that's needed.
So the CD areas are really areas that you're essentially recycling.
Right.
If you look at the map over there, there's a big patch of yellow area, I would say about 250 square miles that's CD-eligible area, and we will be identifying that as a neighborhood planning area.
For the rest of the area outside that and inside the ETJ, we will call it the sector planning area.
The sector planning area will be...
